      <body>I think it's not a big issue whether they can be optional. But it's good to give the app developer control about where in the route precedence a plugin's routes go. Desert does this with a way to embed plugin routes within the main routes file.  e.g.:

@@@ ruby
map.resources :posts
map.routes_from_plugin(:user)
map.namespace :admin do # ...
@@@

Controlling order can be important when you've got wildcards to worry about. Of course there's a tradeoff between the convenience of a plugin being able to add its own routes and the ability to control precedence. We've built a lot of apps using Desert and we find the control preferable to convenience.</body>
      <body-html>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;I think it's not a big issue whether they can be optional. But
it's good to give the app developer control about where in the
route precedence a plugin's routes go. Desert does this with a way
to embed plugin routes within the main routes file. e.g.:&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;ruby&quot;&gt;
map.resources :posts
map.routes_from_plugin(:user)
map.namespace :admin do # ...
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Controlling order can be important when you've got wildcards to
worry about. Of course there's a tradeoff between the convenience
of a plugin being able to add its own routes and the ability to
control precedence. We've built a lot of apps using Desert and we
find the control preferable to convenience.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</body-html>
